About The Dataset¶

Description¶

  • Author: Volker Lohweg (University of Applied Sciences, Ostwestfalen-Lippe)
  • OpenML Source: OpenML: Bank Note Authentication

Dataset is about distinguishing genuine and forged banknotes. Data was extracted from images that were taken from genuine and forged banknote-like specimens. For digitization, an industrial camera which is usually used for printing inspection, was used. The final images had 400 x 400 pixels. Due to the object lens and distance to the investigated object gray-scale pictures with a resolution of about 660 dpi was gained. After which Wavelet Transform tool was used to extract features from these images.

Attribute Information¶

  • V1: Variance: variance of Wavelet Transformed image (continuous)
  • V2: Skewness: Skewness of Wavelet Transformed image (continuous)
  • V3: Curtosis: Curtosis of Wavelet Transformed image (continuous)
  • V4: Entropy: Entropy of image (continuous)
  • Class: Presumably 0 for genuine and 1 for forged bank notes. (Target Variable)

  1. Variance: The variance is a measure of the spread of a distribution. In the context of the Bank Note Authentication dataset, the variance feature measures the variance of the wavelet-transformed image of the banknote. A higher variance indicates that the wavelet coefficients have a larger spread and that the image has more details. In other words, higher variance values may indicate that the banknote is more complex and harder to counterfeit.

  2. Skewness: Skewness is a measure of the asymmetry of a distribution. In the Bank Note Authentication dataset, the skewness feature measures the skewness of the wavelet-transformed image of the banknote. A positive skewness value indicates that the distribution of the wavelet coefficients is skewed to the right, while a negative skewness value indicates that the distribution is skewed to the left. A zero skewness value indicates that the distribution is symmetric. Skewed distributions may indicate that the banknote is counterfeit because it may be difficult to replicate the exact shape of the genuine banknote.

  3. Kurtosis: Kurtosis is a measure of the "peakedness" of a distribution. In the Bank Note Authentication dataset, the kurtosis feature measures the kurtosis of the wavelet-transformed image of the banknote. A higher kurtosis value indicates that the distribution of the wavelet coefficients has a sharper peak and heavier tails than a normal distribution. A lower kurtosis value indicates that the distribution is flatter and more spread out. High kurtosis values may indicate that the banknote is genuine because genuine banknotes have specific printing patterns that create these sharper peaks.

  4. Entropy: Entropy is a measure of the randomness or uncertainty of a distribution. In the Bank Note Authentication dataset, the entropy feature measures the entropy of the image. A higher entropy value indicates that the image is more complex and has more information, while a lower entropy value indicates that the image is simpler and has less information. High entropy values may indicate that the banknote is genuine because genuine banknotes have specific patterns and designs that create a higher level of complexity in the image. On the other hand, low entropy values may indicate that the banknote is counterfeit because it may have a simpler design that is easier to replicate.

Training Testing And Implementing KNN Classifier¶

The above code performs classification on a dataset using the k-Nearest Neighbors (KNN) algorithm. Here's what it does step by step:

  • The first line selects four columns ("Variance", "Skewness", "Curtosis", and "Entropy") from the dataset "data" and assigns them to the variable X. It also selects the "class" column and assigns it to the variable y.
  • The second line splits the dataset into training and testing sets. The training set contains 70% of the data, while the testing set contains 30%. The random_state parameter ensures that the split is reproducible.
  • The third and fourth lines standardize the data in X_train and X_test using the StandardScaler() function. This scales the features so that they have a mean of 0 and a standard deviation of 1. This is a common preprocessing step for many machine learning algorithms.
  • The fifth line creates a KNN classifier object with k=2 and a uniform weighting scheme.
  • The sixth line fits the KNN classifier on the training data using the fit() method.
  • The seventh line makes predictions on the testing data using the predict() method of the KNN classifier.
  • The eighth and ninth lines print the accuracy score of the model and its train and test scores.
  • The accuracy score is a measure of how many predictions the model got right out of all the predictions made.

The KNN Classifier Train Score measures the accuracy of the model on the training data, while the KNN Classifier Validation Score measures its accuracy on the testing data. These scores can be used to evaluate the performance of the model and tune its hyperparameters.

In [17]:
X = data[["Variance","Skewness","Curtosis","Entropy"]]
y = data['class']

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size = 0.3, random_state = 0)

# standardize data
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_train = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test = scaler.transform(X_test)

KNNclassifier = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors = 2, weights ='uniform' )

KNNclassifier.fit(X_train, y_train)
prediction = KNNclassifier.predict(X_test)

print("Accuracy:", accuracy_score(prediction, y_test))
print('KNN Classifier Train Score: ', KNNclassifier.score(X_train, y_train))
print('KNN Classifier Validation Score: ', KNNclassifier.score(X_test, y_test))

The code above generates an ROC (Receiver Operating Characteristic) curve to evaluate the performance of the KNN classifier on the test set. Here's how it works:

  • The first line uses the predict_proba method of the KNN classifier to get the predicted probabilities of the positive class (banknote is counterfeit) for the test set. The [:, 1] indexing is used to extract only the probabilities of the positive class.
  • The second line calculates the ROC curve using the roc_curve function from the sklearn.metrics module. This function takes the true labels (y_test) and predicted probabilities (y_pred_proba) as inputs and returns three arrays: fpr (false positive rate), tpr (true positive rate), and thresholds. The false positive rate is defined as the number of false positives divided by the sum of true negatives and false positives, while the true positive rate is defined as the number of true positives divided by the sum of true positives and false negatives.
  • The third line calculates the AUC (Area Under the Curve) score of the ROC curve using the roc_auc_score function from the sklearn.metrics module. The AUC score is a measure of how well the classifier can distinguish between the positive and negative classes. An AUC score of 1.0 indicates perfect performance, while a score of 0.5 indicates random performance.
  • The fourth to seventh lines plot the ROC curve.
In [21]:
# Get the predicted probabilities of the positive class on the testing data
y_pred_proba = KNNclassifier.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]
# Calculate the ROC curve and AUC score
fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, y_pred_proba)
auc_score = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred_proba)
# Plot the ROC curve
plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label = f'AUC={auc_score:.2f}')
plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'k--', label = 'Random')

plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')

plt.legend()

Preparing Data for performing Training, Hyper parameter tuning, Creating Endpoint and establishing Serverless Inferencing.¶

Amazon SageMaker is a fully-managed service that provides developers and data scientists with the ability to build, train, and deploy machine learning models quickly and easily. It offers a range of features and tools that allow users to streamline the machine learning development process, from data labeling and preprocessing to model training and deployment. In this context, let's discuss the following terms with respect to AWS SageMaker:

  1. Training job: A training job is the process of running a machine learning algorithm on a dataset to create a trained model. In AWS SageMaker, you can create a training job by providing your data and code to the platform, which then spins up a cluster of machines to run the job. During the training process, SageMaker automatically manages the hardware resources and optimizes the training process to achieve the best possible performance.

  2. Hyperparameter tuning: Hyperparameters are parameters that control the behavior of the machine learning algorithm, such as the learning rate, batch size, and number of hidden layers. Hyperparameter tuning is the process of finding the best set of hyperparameters for a given machine learning problem. In AWS SageMaker, you can use the built-in hyperparameter tuning feature to automatically search for the best set of hyperparameters for your model. SageMaker performs the tuning process by running multiple training jobs with different hyperparameter values and selecting the best one based on a defined metric, such as accuracy or F1 score.

  3. Inferencing: Inferencing is the process of using a trained machine learning model to make predictions on new data. In AWS SageMaker, you can use the trained model to perform inferencing on new data by deploying the model to an endpoint. The endpoint provides a web service interface that allows you to send requests to the model and receive predictions in real-time.

  4. Endpoint: An endpoint is a web service interface that allows you to deploy a trained machine learning model to the cloud and make predictions on new data. In AWS SageMaker, you can create an endpoint by deploying your trained model to a SageMaker-managed infrastructure. Once the endpoint is created, you can use it to perform real-time inferencing on new data.

  5. Serverless Inference: Serverless inference is a deployment option for machine learning models that allows you to perform inferencing without having to manage servers or infrastructure. In AWS SageMaker, you can use the serverless inference feature to deploy your trained model to an AWS Lambda function, which can then be invoked via an API Gateway endpoint. This approach allows you to scale your inferencing workload dynamically based on demand and eliminates the need for managing servers or infrastructure.

In summary, AWS SageMaker provides a range of features and tools that allow you to streamline the machine learning development process, from training and hyperparameter tuning to inferencing and deployment. The platform automates many of the tedious and time-consuming tasks associated with machine learning development, allowing you to focus on building and improving your models. With its built-in integration with other AWS services and support for popular machine learning frameworks, AWS SageMaker is a powerful tool for data scientists and developers looking to build and deploy machine learning models at scale.

Training Job¶

AWS SageMaker is a cloud-based machine learning service provided by Amazon Web Services. It is a fully managed service that provides developers and data scientists with the tools to build, train, and deploy machine learning models at scale. One of the core functionalities of SageMaker is its ability to perform training jobs.

A training job is the process of training a machine learning model on a dataset to generate a trained model that can be used for inference. Training a machine learning model involves two key components: the training data and the machine learning algorithm. The training data is used to teach the model to recognize patterns and make predictions, while the machine learning algorithm is used to optimize the model's performance.

In SageMaker, training jobs can be performed using a variety of built-in algorithms or custom algorithms. These algorithms include linear regression, logistic regression, K-means clustering, and neural networks. Training jobs can also be performed on SageMaker using frameworks such as TensorFlow, PyTorch, and MXNet.

The training process in SageMaker is performed in a number of steps. First, the training data is loaded into Amazon S3, which is a highly scalable object storage service offered by AWS. Next, the training data is preprocessed using a pre-processing script or a built-in SageMaker algorithm. This preprocessing step involves tasks such as data cleaning, feature engineering, and data normalization. The preprocessed data is then split into training and validation sets. The training set is used to train the model, while the validation set is used to measure the model's performance during training.

Once the data has been preprocessed and split, the training job can be initiated. During the training job, the machine learning algorithm uses the training data to optimize the model's parameters. The training job can be configured with a variety of hyperparameters such as learning rate, batch size, and regularization. These hyperparameters can be tuned to optimize the performance of the model.

During the training process, SageMaker provides real-time monitoring of the training job using Amazon CloudWatch. This allows developers to track the progress of the training job and monitor key performance metrics such as accuracy, loss, and learning rate. SageMaker also supports distributed training, which allows the training job to be distributed across multiple instances to speed up the training process.

Once the training job is complete, SageMaker generates a trained model artifact that can be used for inference. This trained model artifact can be stored in Amazon S3 or deployed directly to an endpoint for real-time inference.

Overall, training jobs in SageMaker provide developers and data scientists with a powerful and scalable platform for training machine learning models. The ability to use built-in algorithms, frameworks, and custom algorithms, combined with the ability to configure hyperparameters and monitor the training process in real-time, make SageMaker a versatile and powerful tool for machine learning development.

Hyper Parameter Tuning¶

Hyperparameter tuning is the process of optimizing the hyperparameters of a machine learning model to achieve the best possible performance. Hyperparameters are parameters that are set before the training process begins, and they determine the behavior of the machine learning algorithm during training. In AWS SageMaker, hyperparameter tuning is performed using the Automatic Model Tuning feature.

Automatic Model Tuning is a SageMaker feature that automatically searches for the best hyperparameters for a machine learning model. It does this by performing multiple training jobs with different hyperparameter configurations, and then selecting the configuration that produces the best performance. This process is repeated until the best hyperparameters have been identified.

The process of hyperparameter tuning in SageMaker begins by specifying the range of hyperparameters that should be explored during the tuning process. This is done by specifying a hyperparameter tuning job configuration, which includes the range of hyperparameters to explore, the objective metric to optimize, and the search strategy to use.

SageMaker provides a range of search strategies that can be used for hyperparameter tuning, including Bayesian optimization, random search, and grid search. Each search strategy has its own strengths and weaknesses, and the choice of strategy will depend on the specific problem being solved.

Once the hyperparameter tuning job is started, SageMaker automatically creates multiple training jobs with different hyperparameter configurations. Each training job runs on a separate instance, which allows the tuning process to be parallelized and accelerated.

During the tuning process, SageMaker monitors the performance of each training job and records the objective metric, such as accuracy or loss. The objective metric is used to determine which hyperparameter configuration produces the best performance.

Once the tuning process is complete, SageMaker selects the hyperparameter configuration that produced the best performance and generates a trained model artifact. This trained model artifact can be used for inference, and can be deployed to an endpoint for real-time inference.

Hyperparameter tuning in SageMaker provides developers and data scientists with a powerful tool for optimizing the performance of machine learning models. By automating the process of hyperparameter tuning, SageMaker allows developers to focus on other aspects of model development, such as data preprocessing and feature engineering.

Overall, hyperparameter tuning in SageMaker is a powerful feature that enables developers and data scientists to optimize the performance of their machine learning models. By automating the process of hyperparameter tuning, SageMaker simplifies the process of model development and makes it easier to achieve high levels of performance.

import bokeh
import bokeh.io

bokeh.io.output_notebook()
from bokeh.plotting import figure, show
from bokeh.models import HoverTool


class HoverHelper:
    def __init__(self, tuning_analytics):
        self.tuner = tuning_analytics

    def hovertool(self):
        tooltips = [
            ("FinalObjectiveValue", "@FinalObjectiveValue"),
            ("TrainingJobName", "@TrainingJobName"),
        ]
        for k in self.tuner.tuning_ranges.keys():
            tooltips.append((k, "@{%s}" % k))

        ht = HoverTool(tooltips=tooltips)
        return ht

    def tools(self, standard_tools="pan,crosshair,wheel_zoom,zoom_in,zoom_out,undo,reset"):
        return [self.hovertool(), standard_tools]


hover = HoverHelper(tuner)

p = figure(width=900, height=400, tools=hover.tools(), x_axis_type="datetime")
p.circle(source=df, x="TrainingStartTime", y="FinalObjectiveValue")
show(p)

ranges = tuner.tuning_ranges
figures = []
for hp_name, hp_range in ranges.items():
    categorical_args = {}
    if hp_range.get("Values"):
        # This is marked as categorical.  Check if all options are actually numbers.
        def is_num(x):
            try:
                float(x)
                return 1
            except:
                return 0

        vals = hp_range["Values"]
        if sum([is_num(x) for x in vals]) == len(vals):
            # Bokeh has issues plotting a "categorical" range that's actually numeric, so plot as numeric
            print("Hyperparameter %s is tuned as categorical, but all values are numeric" % hp_name)
        else:
            # Set up extra options for plotting categoricals.  A bit tricky when they're actually numbers.
            categorical_args["x_range"] = vals

    # Now plot it
    p = figure(
        width=500,
        height=500,
        title="Objective vs %s" % hp_name,
        tools=hover.tools(),
        x_axis_label=hp_name,
        y_axis_label=objective_name,
        **categorical_args,
    )
    p.circle(source=df, x=hp_name, y="FinalObjectiveValue")
    figures.append(p)
show(bokeh.layouts.Column(*figures))

Endpoint Configuration and Endpoint Creation¶

An endpoint is a web service that allows you to deploy a trained machine learning model for real-time inference. In AWS SageMaker, endpoint configuration and endpoint creation are two important steps in deploying a machine learning model to an endpoint.

Endpoint Configuration:¶

An endpoint configuration is a set of parameters that define how a deployed model should be run. These parameters include the instance type, the number of instances, and the type of data that can be sent to the endpoint.

SageMaker provides a range of instance types that can be used for endpoint configuration, each with its own characteristics in terms of performance, memory, and cost. The choice of instance type will depend on the specific requirements of the machine learning model being deployed.

In addition to instance type, endpoint configuration also includes the number of instances that should be used for inference. This can range from a single instance to a cluster of instances, depending on the workload and the desired level of performance.

Finally, endpoint configuration also includes the data format that should be used when sending data to the endpoint. This is important because different machine learning models require different data formats, and using the wrong format can result in errors or poor performance.

Endpoint Creation:¶

Once the endpoint configuration is defined, the next step is to create the endpoint itself. This is done by selecting the model to be deployed, the endpoint configuration to use, and the deployment type. SageMaker supports two deployment types: Real-time and Batch.

Real-time deployment is used for applications that require immediate response times, such as chatbots or real-time fraud detection systems. In this case, data is sent to the endpoint in real-time, and the endpoint responds with a prediction or a decision.

Batch deployment, on the other hand, is used for applications that can tolerate longer processing times, such as batch processing of large datasets. In this case, data is sent to the endpoint in batches, and the endpoint processes the data in bulk.

Once the deployment type is selected, SageMaker automatically creates the endpoint, which can be accessed through a web service API. The endpoint is a fully-managed service, which means that AWS takes care of all aspects of deployment, scaling, and management.

Endpoint creation in SageMaker is a powerful feature that allows developers and data scientists to deploy machine learning models for real-time inference. By automating the process of endpoint creation, SageMaker makes it easy to deploy and manage machine learning models at scale, and provides a reliable and secure platform for real-time inference.

In conclusion, endpoint configuration and endpoint creation are two important steps in deploying a machine learning model to an endpoint in AWS SageMaker. By defining the endpoint configuration and selecting the appropriate deployment type, developers and data scientists can easily deploy machine learning models for real-time inference, and take advantage of the powerful features and scalability of the SageMaker platform.

Serverless Inference¶

Serverless inference is a method of running machine learning (ML) models in a scalable, flexible, and cost-effective way without the need for maintaining infrastructure or capacity. AWS Sagemaker provides an option for serverless inference, which enables deploying machine learning models on-demand and only paying for what is used. In this note, we will provide a detailed overview of serverless inference with respect to AWS Sagemaker.

AWS Sagemaker is a fully-managed service that makes it easier to build, train, and deploy machine learning models at scale. Sagemaker provides several options for deploying machine learning models, including real-time inference and batch inference. Real-time inference is used for applications that require low latency, where predictions are made in real-time as data is being generated. Batch inference is used for applications where a large amount of data needs to be processed, where predictions are made in batches.

Serverless inference is a new feature of AWS Sagemaker, which allows deploying machine learning models without provisioning or managing any infrastructure. It is an ideal solution for applications that have variable demand and are cost-sensitive. In serverless inference, the machine learning model is deployed as an endpoint, and the service is charged based on the number of requests and the duration of the inference. AWS Sagemaker automatically scales the number of instances up and down based on the demand, ensuring that the endpoint is always available to serve requests.

To use serverless inference, you first need to train a machine learning model using Sagemaker's built-in algorithms or by bringing your own algorithms. Once the model is trained, you can deploy it as an endpoint using the Sagemaker console, AWS CLI, or SDKs. When deploying the model, you specify the number of instances and the instance type. AWS Sagemaker supports a wide range of instance types, including CPU, GPU, and memory-optimized instances. You can also specify the minimum and maximum number of instances that should be running to handle incoming requests.

Once the endpoint is created, you can start sending requests to the endpoint using an API Gateway, an HTTP client, or any other tool that can make HTTP requests. When a request is made, AWS Sagemaker automatically routes the request to an available instance and returns the prediction. If the demand increases, AWS Sagemaker automatically adds more instances to handle the load. Similarly, if the demand decreases, AWS Sagemaker automatically scales down the number of instances, reducing the cost.

AWS Sagemaker provides several features to monitor and optimize the performance of the endpoint. You can monitor the endpoint's health, including the number of requests, latency, and error rates, using Amazon CloudWatch. You can also configure auto-scaling policies to scale the endpoint up and down based on the number of requests or the average latency. Additionally, you can use AWS Sagemaker's A/B testing feature to compare the performance of multiple models deployed as endpoints and choose the best-performing model.

Serverless inference is an ideal solution for applications with variable demand and cost-sensitive applications. With serverless inference, you can deploy machine learning models without provisioning or managing any infrastructure, and pay only for what you use. AWS Sagemaker provides a range of features to monitor and optimize the performance of the endpoint, making it easier to deploy and manage machine learning models at scale.

In conclusion, serverless inference with AWS Sagemaker provides a scalable, flexible, and cost-effective way to deploy machine learning models without the need for maintaining infrastructure or capacity. It is an ideal solution for applications with variable demand and cost-sensitive applications. With AWS Sagemaker's built-in algorithms, model training, and deployment tools, it is easy to get started with serverless inference and deploy machine learning models at scale.
